nd John Malkovich, the very American press agent and social maverick Billy “Silver Dollar” Baxter, and the stylishly plunging necklines of yore. He also comments on the trajectory of the festival itself and the “enormous happiness” of sitting, anonymous and quiet, in an ordinary French café. And, of course, he talks movies. Illustrated with Ebert’s charming sketches of the festival and featuring both a new foreword by Martin Scorsese and a new postscript by Ebert about an eventful 1997 dinner with Scorsese at Cannes, Two Weeks in the Midday Sun is a small treasure, a window onto the mind of this connoisseur of criticism and satire, a man always so funny, so un-phony, so completely, unabashedly himself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFilm festivals. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  acannes film festival, cinema, fellini, coppola, charles bukowski, isabella rossellini, john malkovich, billy baxter, fashion, criticism, celebrity interviews, travel writing, france, nonfiction, essays, social commentary, fame, sketches, princess diana, drawings, barbara hershey, premieres, performing arts, biography, profile, appreciation, behind the scenes, entertainment, travelogue.1 aScorsese, Martin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226314570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226314570/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles